*Unlocking Granular Control for Day & Date Surges*


Every network experiences peaks that don=E2=80=99t always last an entire da=
y. Some
spikes happen only for a few hours and until now, day and date level surges
treated everything as a full-day event.

With this update, you can now define *complex Day and Date surges* that
reflect how your operations actually behave, bringing precision and
flexibility into time-based pricing.
Why We Built This

Previously, when a surge was set at a *Day* or *Date* level, it applied for
the *entire 24 hours*. This created:

   -

   Overextended surges during non-peak hours
   -

   Manual workarounds for short-term spikes
   -

   Pricing that didn=E2=80=99t align with real demand patterns



This update brings that hidden flexibility directly into your hands.
What=E2=80=99s New


Time Slot Based Surges

You can now define *surge pricing for specific time slots within a day or a
date*.

Instead of being locked to all-day surges, you can choose exactly *when* a
surge should apply, whether that=E2=80=99s a one-hour lunch rush, an evenin=
g spike,
or a short window during a special date.


For both *Day-level* and *Date-level* surges, you can now:

   -

   Select precise *start and end times*
   -

   Apply surge pricing only within those windows
   -

   Use  *Flat Rate* and *Percentage* for each time slot



This gives you fine-grained control over pricing during the moments that
matter most, ensuring surges activate only when demand actually peaks =E2=
=80=94 not
when operations are running normally.


Your surge strategy is no longer tied to full days.

It now moves with time.

Layered Surges

For both *Day* and *Date* level surges, you can now choose to apply pricing
in three ways:

   -

   *For the entire day or date*
   -

   *For specific time-slots within a day or date*
   -

   *Or both*, with:
   -

      A *base surge* applied to the full day/date
      -

      An *additional surge* applied only to a defined time period



This allows you to create layered pricing that adapts to both general and
peak-hour demand.
What This Means For You

You can now match your surge strategy to how your network actually runs.

This means:

   -

   Special dates can behave differently at different times
   -

   Surge logic becomes cleaner, more predictable, and more profitable



Your pricing finally moves with your business instead of against it.
